quran[11]{c,v,t,f}:
18,5,"a thing about which they have no knowledge, {1} neither they nor their ancestors. Dreadful is the word that comes out of their mouths. What they utter is merely a lie.",footnotes:1:“Dreadful is the word” That one is the son of God
18,6,"(O Muhammad), if they do not believe in this Message, {1} you will perhaps torment yourself to death with grief, sorrowing over them.",footnotes:1:This refers to the real cause of the anxiety of the Prophet (peace be upon him) at the time of the revelation of this Surah. It clearly shows that the Prophet (peace be upon him) did not grieve at the persecution from which he and his companions were suffering but at the deviation and moral degeneration of his people. What was consuming him was that
18,7,"Surely We have made all that is on the earth an embellishment for it in order to test people as to who of them is better in conduct."
18,8,"In the ultimate, We shall reduce all that is on the earth to a barren plain. {1}",footnotes:1:(Ayat 6 )was addressed to the Prophet (peace be upon him)
18,9,"Do you think that the people of the Cave {1} and the Inscription {2} were one of Our wondrous signs? {3}",footnotes:1:The Arabic word Kahf literally means a vast cave.|178912:There is a difference of opinion about the meaning of arraqim. Some companions and their followers opined that it was the name of that habitation where this event took place and that it was situated somewhere between Aylah and Palestine. There are other commentators who take it to mean the inscription that had been set up at the cave as a memorial to the sleepers of the cave. Abul Kalam Azad
18,10,"When those youths sought refuge in the Cave and said: "Our Lord! Grant us mercy from Yourself and provide for us rectitude in our affairs.""
18,11,"We lulled them to sleep in that cave for a number of years"
18,12,"and then roused them so that We might see which of the two parties could best tell the length of their stay."
18,13,"We narrate to you their true story. {1} They were a party of young men who had faith in their Lord, and We increased them in guidance {2}",footnotes:1:The resemblance between the two versions is so close that even the name of the companion whom the sleepers sent to the city to buy food after waking up has been mentioned as Jamblicha by the Muslim scholars and Jamblichus by Gibbon. The details of the story in both the versions are also similar which are briefly as follows.|178914:The oldest evidence of this story is found in a homily written in Syriac by Jacob of Sarug
18,14,"and strengthened their hearts when they stood up and proclaimed: "Our Lord is the Lord of the heavens and the earth. We shall call upon no other god beside Him; (for if we did so), we shall be uttering a blasphemy.""
  18,15,"(Then they conferred among themselves and said): "These men, our own people, have taken others as gods beside Him: why do they not bring any clear evidence that they indeed are gods? Who can be more unjust than he who foists a lie on Allah?"